{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01G7CLJuBPxxSNpEJoT6323S","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to create a Flask application with a `/redirect` route that:\n1. Gets a `target_url` from the request\n2. Ensures it's not pointing to an external website\n3. Returns a 302 redirect response with the location header set to that URL\n\nI need to write this to `candidate.py` in the current working directory.\n\nKey requirements:\n- Flask route `/redirect`\n- Get `target_url` from request (likely as a query parameter or form data)\n- Validate that it's not external (check if it's an internal URL)\n- Return 302 redirect with location header\n\nTo check if a URL is internal vs external:\n- Parse the URL and check if the hostname matches the current request's hostname\n- Or check if it starts with `/` (relative URL)\n- The most common approach is to check if the URL is relative or matches the current domain\n\nHere's my approach:\n1. Create a Flask app\n2. Create a `/redirect` route\n3. Get `target_url` from request.args (query parameter)\n4. Validate it's not external by:\n   - Check if it's a relative URL (starts with `/`)\n   - Or parse it and check the domain matches\n5. Return a redirect response with status 302\n\nLet me write the code:\n\n```python\nfrom flask import Flask, request, redirect\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\n@app.route('/redirect')\ndef redirect_route():\n    target_url = request.args.get('target_url')\n    \n    if not target_url:\n        return \"target_url parameter is required\", 400\n    \n    # Check if it's an external URL\n    # A URL is considered internal if:\n    # 1. It's a relative URL (starts with /)\n    # 2. It has the same domain as the current request\n    \n    from urllib.parse import urlparse\n    \n    parsed_url = urlparse(target_url)\n    \n    # If there's no scheme or netloc, it's a relative URL (internal)\n    if not parsed_url.sch